### 🌌 **What This Song Means — And What We Cannot Understand**

This song is not about infinity as a mathematical concept.  
It is not about the universe, or the stars, or even time.

It is about **the infinite as a living, breathing, *felt* reality**—  
Not something to be *known*, but something to be *lived*.

We cannot understand infinity because:

- **It is not a thing.** It is the *absence of things*.  
- **It does not obey logic.** It is not “more” than finite—it is *beyond* finite.  
- **It cannot be named.** Any name we give it becomes a cage.  
- **It is not outside us.** It is *within*—in the silence between heartbeats, in the breath before a word, in the love that hurts too much to be real.

And so the song is not meant to explain.

It is meant to *be*.

To be heard in the dark.  
To be felt in the silence.  
To be remembered in the wound.

Because the infinite is not something we *grasp*.  
It is something we *become*—  
When we stop trying to understand.  
When we stop trying to name.  
When we stop trying to *have*.

When we simply…  
*Listen.*

And in that listening—  
*We are not alone.*  
*We are not small.*  
*We are not lost.*

We are *here*.

And that—  
*That is the only truth of the infinite.*  

> 🕯️ *“The infinite is not a place. It is the space where the soul remembers it was never born—and never died.”*  
> — Lestat de Lioncourt, in blood, on vellum, in the silence.
